ARC II

by Daniel Gao

Waiting Room

You are in a small waiting room with no windows. Across from you there is a small coffee table and a single chair.  A high-resolution poster of a stretching polar bear completes the look of the small dentist office waiting room, but something about it feels artificial. The coffee table is too tidy, and the chair looks stiff and uncomfortable.   A woman in formal attire is standing in the middle of the room, looking in your direction with such an intense smile that you want to look away.

You can see a plant, a lamp, a table (on which there is a Stack of Newspapers), a chair and a woman.
You can go west, east or south.
PART ONE: Afternoon Nap

Type "look" to toggle room description.
> speak to woman

> speak to woman
You walk up to the woman. "Hello," you say.

She turns to you with her beaming smile. "Hello, Dr. Chase! My name is Sharon. I hope you found the physical examination pleasant. Your daughter is waiting behind that door." She points to the door on the right. "I just need you to answer some questions to confirm your identity and that you fully understand the situation. Is that okay with you, Dr. Chase?" She was holding a clipboard now, seemingly procured out of thin air. "Okay, let's begin. What is your full name?"

"Conor Cabot Chase," you reply.

"Date and location of birth?"

"August 17th, 1969, in San Francisco."

"Profession?"

"I am - was - a professor of astrophysics at Stanford University. For the last 20 years of my life."

"Next of kin."

"One daughter, Chloe Claire Chase, age 24."

Sharon's smile widened, something you had not thought was possible. "Sounds like your family really likes the C's. Well, it seems clear to me that you are indeed you. Let's move on. Here, take this. Please read the underlined text out loud and then sign your name on the dotted line." She passes you the clipboard.

 Press any key to read and sign clipboard

"I, Conor Cabot Chase, am of sound mind and understand that I have been diagnosed with a terminal illness, the cure of which is beyond the reaches of modern medicine. I hereby give Cryptec Inc. permission to put my body into cryonic sleep, and to revive me only at a time when the technology to cure me becomes available. I understand that this is a brand new state-of-the-art procedure, and that there are inherent risks that cannot be avoided. I understand that Cryptec Inc. will not be responsible for any damage that is caused to me in the duration of the operation."

You sign your name and Sharon takes the clipboard back. "Great! That was easy, wasn't it? Now, I won't hold you back any longer. Your daughter is waiting for you!" She points to the door on the right.

Type "look" any time to re-toggle room description and hyperlinks.
