Meeting Room

This room is slightly larger than the one you just stepped out of, and it looks as if someone had put in an effort to make it seem cozy. The floor is carpeted and there is a black couch facing yet another coffee table. To your left is a bookcase, empty except for a couple of hardcovers strewn across the top row.  There is a woman sitting on the couch with her back towards you, her shoulders moving up and down in short bursts, as if she were sobbing. It's your daughter, Chloe. She doesn't seem to have heard you come in.

You can see a bookshelf, a couch, a table and Chloe Chase.
You can go west or north.
> speak to chloe

> speak to chloe
"Chloe?" Your voice is barely more than a whisper.

The young woman on the sofa suddenly sits up straight. She stands and turns to look at you, her eyes red but her lips spread out in a huge smile. "Dad!" she says, and runs into your arms. You hold her there, steadying yourself against her body. She is so warm, so tough, so strong. You don't want to let go, don't want to look into her eyes and acknowledge, to the both of you, that you might never see her again.

"Dad, you will be okay. I promise. Dr. Schneider is a brilliant man, and I have the utmost trust in him. I have a feeling that I will see you again very soon. Great things are happening at Cryptec, you know. Oh, I almost forgot." She takes off the necklace that she is wearing, a golden turtle on a silver chain. "You gave this to me for my twenty-first birthday. I want you to keep this, to wear it when you . . . sleep. It would mean a lot to me." She drapes it around your neck, and when her fingers touch your skin you feel shivers up your spine. "There," she says. "I think it looks much better on you anyway."

"Chloe," you say, "there's something you're not telling me. Don't give me that look; I've known you for all your life, I know what you're like when you're trying to keep something from me. Is it bad news? Go on, I can handle it."

Chloe looks down at her feet, frowning. "I didn't want to alarm you. It's probably nothing. It's just . . . something seems off about this disease, the Grey Death. It's not just that it's fatal . . . we've eliminated so many fatal diseases in the past, like yellow fever and smallpox. The way that the Grey Death spreads makes no sense. It doesn't pass from person to person, and yet more cases are being diagnosed every day. It's just not right. I'm sure that I'm just being paranoid - after all, I am new to this kind of stuff. I don't have Dr. Schneider's experience." Before you can answer, she hugs you again, squeezing all the wind out of you. "If I don't go soon, I'll never go," she mumbles, her face still in your chest. She tiptoes and kisses you on the cheek.

"Have a good time," you say. "And you have the best time," she replies, and you both smile at the inside joke. Then, she turns to the northern door, which opens with a beep as she swipes her employee card on the reader. Before you know it, she is gone.

