Hallway

You are in a long, white hallway, stretching out before you, seemingly without end. The floor is tiled and so clean that you can see your blurred reflection in it. The walls are empty and bare.

The door closes behind you with a click. You stand there, not sure if you are expected to walk forward, when you hear footsteps coming toward you. A clean-shaven man, around seventy years of age and wearing a white lab coat, appears from the depths of the hallway, like a chameleon emerging from camouflage. He holds out his hand. His manner is gentle and polite.

"Hi, Dr. Chase. My name is Dr. Carl Schneider. It is a pleasure to finally meet you."

"A pleasure to meet you too," you say. "My daughter has told me so much about you."

Dr. Schneider coughs lightly into his elbow. He looks at you over his glasses, and you feel as if he is talking down to you, like a parent trying to comfort a crying child. "I don't want you to worry at all, Dr. Chase. You are, of course, aware that you are about to be the first person to undergo cryogenic sleep. Naturally there will be some risk. But I want to assure you, Dr. Chase, that we will do everything in our power to keep you safe, alive, and healthy." He starts to move down the hallway and you follow behind. "Your daughter, by the way, has an extraordinary medical mind; she is without doubt the most brilliant researcher in my lab. You should be proud. Not to mention anything about her stubbornness and determination: from the first day she heard about the project, she insisted on the possibility of having you as our first trial subject. I told her about the risks, the conflict of interest . . . but she just wouldn't let up. She is a headstrong woman." He smiles. "My daugher is very much the same. I tried my best to get her to go to medical school, but she just wouldn't give up on her childhood dream."

"And what dream was that?" you ask.

"She wanted to be an astronaut."

 Press any key to follow Dr. Schneider

The doctor offers you his arm, but you tell him you can walk on your own. "Right now, I'm taking you to the sleep chamber. Dr. Chase, have you ever been under general anesthesia before? Well, this is going to be just like that. No pain, no disorientation whatsoever. You're going to close your eyes, and then open then again. Easy as that. It will just be like an afternoon nap." You finally reach the end of the hallway. A small, wooden door blocks the way. The doctor opens it and you follow him in.

Bedroom

The room is small and tidy. A twin-sized bed with grey covers occupies one corner, and a working desk occupies another. A tall, sturdy wardrobe stands at the foot of the bed, open just wide enough for you to see the suits hanging inside. An upright lamp illuminates the windowless bedroom. The walls are bare, except for a single poster, a colorized photograph of the Milky Way. A luscious carpet covers the floor. There is a folded letter on the table. There is a white envelope sitting on the table.

You can see a bed, a desk (on which there is a letter from Zach), a wardrobe, a chair, a lamp, an envelope and Dr Schneider.
You can go east.

You rub your eyes to make sure you aren't dreaming. The bedroom is a spitting copy of the one in your apartment, minus the window over the Stanford campus. You plop down on the bed, glad to finally give your legs some rest. Dr. Schneider is smiling at you.

"It was Chloe's idea; she thought it would make you feel more comfortable. We even took your actual suits to make it seem more realistic."

"But where are the machinery? The tubes? The capsules?"

Dr. Schneider laughed. "We have all that, of course. But we thought it would be scary for you to see. All you have to do is fall asleep, in your own bed, and we'll handle the rest. When you wake up, you will be in your own bed too, so you won't feel disoriented. I'll give you a moment to take it all in."
> speak to schneider

> speak to schneider
"I'm ready," you say.

Dr. Schneider hands you a small red button on a black cube. "When you're ready to sleep, just press this button. We've already injected anesthetic into your veins, and this activates it."

You shake your head. "I didn't know we could do this already."

Dr. Schneider's eyes are shining through his glasses. "This is nothing compared to the technology that you'll see. Fifty years, a hundred, two hundred . . . it will make what we have now seem like rocks and clubs. We'll be able to go wherever we want, whenever we want, do whatever we want. Maybe even death will be eliminated." He puts a hand on your shoulder. "I won't be able to see all of that, but you will. Enjoy it for me."

Press any key to voice your concerns.

"Wait," you say. "Chloe was worried about something. She said there was something off about the disease, about the way it spreads . . ."

Dr. Schneider coughs again. His expression doesn't change. "You leave the worrying to the experts, Dr. Chase. Cryptec employs some of the best doctors and scientists in the world. You won't get better care anywhere else. Thousands of people would kill to be in your position right now."

You nod reluctantly. "Actually, I was wondering about that too. Why all the secrecy? Why do I have to fake my own death? Wouldn't it comfort the public to know that you guys are working on a cure?"

"Dr. Chase," he says slowly. "Hope can be a dangerous thing. Do you know how much it's going to cost to keep you in cryonic sleep? The unit we have prepared for you is the only one of its kind in the world. We have to observe its effects on you and then make more. That could take years and billions of dollars. Not everyone can afford to hope.

"Let me speak frankly, Dr. Chase. I saw the report from your physical examination, and you are not in good shape. In about two weeks you will lose the ability to walk, and in a month you won't be able to breathe without a tube sticking into your lungs. It is a painful way to die; trust me, I've seen it. This is your only chance to survive."

He sees the look on your face. "If you can't do this for yourself, then do it for Chloe. Do it for science. Don't think too much about questions that you can't answer, Dr. Chase." With that, he turns and walks out of the room. The door shuts with a soft click.

A button has been added to your inventory. Type "inventory" to see what you are carrying.

> press button

> press button
You look at the button, staring back at you with its single red eye. If you press it, you may never wake up again. Are you ready? You tell yourself that you've lived a full life, but the truth is you're afraid of death. A simple, quick press of the button, and then . . . nothingness for eternity. You want so badly to imagine it but you can't. You try to bring up the faces of your late wife and daughter, but you are surprised at how difficult it is. Maybe you should sit here for a while longer. There's no rush, after all.
> press button

> press button
You finger brushes the top of the button. Why did you agree to do this? If you had just died, you would have been out of Chloe's life forever. But now, the thought of you will torment her for the rest of her life, taunt her inability to find a cure for your disease. What if something happens to you? How will she handle the guilt?

You give yourself a mental slap on the cheek. You made Chloe a promise and you are going to follow it through. The time for changing minds has long since passed. Isabelle's death hit her harder than it hit you, and it will be a comfort for her to know that she will never be alone. And what about that bright future that everybody talks about? Perhaps you would like to see it too.

You make up your mind. You are going to press the button.
> press button

> press button
You hold the black box in your hand. It's weight and coldness are somehow comforting. Your life flashes before your eyes; childhood in San Francisco, high school prom, first day at University, meeting Isabelle for the first time . . . holding a crying infant Chloe, receiving your offer of tenure, looking at the stars from the roof of your apartment building and asking it to reveal its mysteries . . . you suppose you've lived as good as a life as anybody could ask for.

You fixate an image in your mind, a picture of Chloe and Isabelle smiling across the table of your favorite restaurant, on your 40th birthday. It's the picture you want to see as you make your leap into eternity. You're thankful that you are able to visualize the image so clearly.

You press the button.

The End of Part One

