Bedroom (Dr. Conor Chase)

The room is small and tidy. A twin-sized bed with grey covers occupies one corner, and a working desk occupies another. A tall, sturdy wardrobe stands at the foot of the bed, open just wide enough for you to see the suits hanging inside. An upright lamp illuminates the windowless bedroom. The walls are bare, except for a single poster, a colorized photograph of the Milky Way. A luscious carpet covers the floor.

You can see a bed, a desk (on which there is a letter ), a wardrobe, a chair and a lamp.
You can go east.

You open your eyes slowly to the familiar yellow tint of your ceiling. You sit up in bed. You have never felt so good before. You had a bad dream, something about diseases and forms on clipboards and long hallways, but now everything is just fine.

You look around. Everything is where it should be, and yet something is not quite right. You've just woken up from an afternoon nap, but there is no sunlight, only the glow of the lamp.

There is no window.

Could it be? Have you arrived at the destination of an undeterminable journey through time? You touch your face, then your hands, then your chest. You feel like yourself, but better. You stand up. You are still wearing same clothes, black jeans and button-down shirt, but all of your lethargy and soreness is gone.

You examine the room again. If the cryonic sleep worked, then why is there nobody here to welcome you into the future? You must have woken up too early. Maybe only a couple of hours have passed. You should go find Dr. Schneider and tell him to give you the anesthetic again.
