South Greenhouse

The hallway opens into a large, cylindrical space, longer and wider than the Stanford football stadium. Along the ceiling is a strip of light, burning into your eyes with the intensity of a small sun. All around you are racks upon racks of plants, rotating silently on unseen tracks, taking their turn to bathe in the light. There are blueberries the size of cherries, and tomatoes so round and perfect and impossibly plump that you can taste their sweetness simply by looking at them. And then there are vegetables and fruits that you don't recognize: yellow triangular prisms covered with hair, orange cubic shapes sticking out of the soil. A single, winding path leads onward, but you cannot see where it ends.  There is a book is lying face-down on the dirt, partially hidden from view by the leaves of a grapevine.

You can see a footprints, a The ABC Murders and a sticker.
You can go south or north.

You don't know what you expected when you saw the word "Greenhouse", but it was not this. You feel yourself trembling. Whatever hope you may have had is gone. This is something of the future, something unimaginable by an astrophysics professor born in the 1960s. How many years has it been? How many? Zach is surely dead. Chloe probably is, too. What have you done? What have you gotten yourself into?
> north

> north

Central Greenhouse

The winding path continues. The greenhouse is so impossibly vast, the ceiling so high, that you forget you are indoors. To your left is a large reservoir, a square of piercing blue, with channels running through the greenhouse in intricate grids. To your amazement, you follow the channels with your eyes and see them run onto the walls and ceiling, unhindered by gravity.  To your right is a small path cut through the plants, leading to a circular clearing. In the middle of the clearing is what appears to be a black tombstone, surrounded by rings of flowers.

You can see a Tombstone.
You can go south or north.
> x tombstone

> x tombstone
You see yourself in the shiny surface of the stone: an old man, hair halfway grey, crow's feet beginning to grow from the corners of your eyes. And yet you see a vitality in that familiar face, the determination of a man who has been given a second chance at life. There are no words on the smooth stone, no name to indicate who lay beneath your feet, no dates to delineate their short stay upon this earth. The flowers, though, are beautiful, each one a different shade from the next. You wish you could name them, but you were never a flower person. You count them. There are exactly fifty-one.

There is a sound coming from further up the path, to the north, a dull kind of thudding, like metal hitting dirt. You stiffen; this is the first sound you've heard since waking up. If there is another person in the greenhouse, they could explain everything, they could take you to see Chloe, if . . . you let that thought drift away unfinished.
> north

> north

North Greenhouse

The greenhouse ends the same way it began. Far in the distance, you see the open space close back onto a single door, where the winding path terminates. Just off the left of the path, in between the blue channels and rotating tracks, is a square plot of earth cut geometrically from its surroundings. The soil in this patch has a lighter shade than the dark, rich soil of the greenhouse.

You are reminded of the garden that you once had, in the backyard of your Palo Alto home. Every weekend, Isabelle would wake up at the crack of dawn to clear the leaves, pull the weeds, and lay mulch around the plants. Sometimes you helped her, but you both knew that it was Isabelle's garden. After she passed, it was neglected and overgrown; you could not bear to admit to yourself that she was gone, that she would never bend over again in that garden, never sweat and smile and wave at you through the window . . .

Despite the advanced technology all around you, the small patch of soil looks as if it has been tended to manually. Modestly-sized tomatoes hang meekly from wooden racks, and pudgy pumpkins are lined up in neat but imperfect rows. There is an old man standing with his back to you, his hair ashen white, his back bent over, clutching a shovel and working furiously on the light soil of the garden. Beside him are a dozen mounds of freshly turned dirt.  Lying on the ground is a body. It's eyes are closed and although you look at it for a while, it does not move.

You can see the Warden, a corpse and a badge.
You can go south or north.
> take badge

> take badge
You pick up the badge and clip it to your pants. You have a feeling it will come in handy.
> speak to warden

> speak to warden
"Who's that?" the old man squints at you. "Nicky? Is that you, Nicky? Where have you been all this time? Look at our garden, look at what I've done. Do you like the pumkpins? We could never get them to grow this big . . ."

"My name is Conor," you say. "Conor Chase. Please, I fell asleep, and when I woke up, I found myself here. . . it was an experiment, part of some trial . . . Dr. Carl Schneider told me that everything woudl be okay . . . do you know Dr. Schneider?" You know that you are jabbering but you can't help it.

The old man squints his eyes. They look milky and grey. "Dr. Chase . . ."

"Please, I need to know. What year is it? Where am I? I need to know if my daughter is okay. Please tell me!"

The old man says nothing. Big, fat teardrops squeeze themselves out from his unseeing eyes, leaving jagged trails down his withered face. His whole body is shaking. "I'm so sorry, so sorry . . . I tried my best. I did everything I could, but I couldn't see, couldn't see . . . my cataracts got worse after Nicky left, but I couldn't tell the captain . . . I couldn't risk losing my job. By the time the power systems came back online, they were all . . . oh God, Nicky, forgive me . . ."

You grasp him by the shoulders, hold him so that his eyes are staring forward into your face. "Calm down," you say, even though your heart is beating at a hundred miles a minute. "Slow down and tell me what happened."

"It was an asteroid that hit us, it must have been. All the sirens were going off and I didn't know what to do . . . oh God . . . I failed everyone. You're the only one left, Dr. Chase. You were the first one, so you were on a different support system . . . I did the best I could.

"Would you forgive me, Dr. Chase? Could you do that for me? "
1: Yes
2: No
> 1
"Of course," you say. "There are many things outside of our control. I'm sure that whatever happened here, it wasn't your fault."

The Warden grasps your hands in his and holds you tightly. His hands are rough and course from a lifetime of gardenwork. "Oh, thank you, thank you. You have no idea what that means to me. You have a big heart, Dr. Chase, to forgive me. But I'm not sure that I can forgive myself. I've served ARC Two faithfully . . . one momentary lapse in fifty-one years, and yet, I let down those who put their lives in my hands."

"Please, if you can just answer some of my questions . . ."

But the Warden has already picked up shovel again. He resumes his work, attacking the earth with less violence this time but the same determination.
