PART THREE: ARC

Press any key to wake up.

You didn't even realize that you had dozed off. What did you dream about? You strain to remember but you can't. Perhaps the same stars that surround you now followed you into the other realm. The thought of it fills you with comfort.

You want to just stay here forever, but you know you can't. There are still so many questions to be answered. You went to sleep underneath the ground, and now you are in space; what happened? And where was Chloe? Speaking of Chloe . . . there was something here that reminded you of her, something recent, but you can't remember what it is . . .

You flail your arms and legs, but you don't seem to move. How can you get to the door? Then, you remember the voice that spoke to you.

"Let me down," you say. "Gravity will now be switched back on," the voice replies, and you find yourself dropping slowly to the walkway. You walk forward and the door slides open.

Archive

You are in a dimly lit, narrow walkway, hemmed in by glass cases that stretch on to your left and right. Inside each case are books of different colors and sizes, packed tightly according to some three-dimensional algorithm, so that not even an inch of empty space is left. Ahead of you, in the center of the walkway, is a wide, black, cylinder. Above it, blue words hang in the air, unsupported by anything that you can see. It reads: "Terminal".

You can see a Terminal.
You can go south or north.
> use terminal

> use terminal
The terminal beeps, and its blue text splinters into holographic options. "What would you like to learn about?" asks the familiar voice.

1: The Selection
2: The Origin of the Grey Death
3: ARC Program
4: Transmission of the Grey Death
> 3
You try to touch the option, but your hand just goes through. "Preparing sources," the voice says. The contents of the cases start moving, shuffling along unseen tracks. A mechanical arm reaches out from above, plucks some books out from behind the cases, and holds them up, open, behind the terminal display. New words appear on the hologram.

The Auto-Restorative Cryonics procedure, or ARC for short, was developed and patented by Cryptec Inc. It was initially conceived as a way to keep subjects alive until a time in the future when a cure for the Grey Death was discovered, but monitoring of subjects revealed that the number of infected cells were reducing without any additional treatment. Cryptec Inc. made the discovery that the virus had a lifespan that was independent of the human host, but that it was much longer than the natural human lifespan. To put it another way, infected humans died faster than the Grey Death did. Freezing the human in a cryonic chamber would extend the lifespan of the human but not that of the virus.

Due to the high cost of cryonic technology and the chaos brought about by World War Three, the ARC program was initiated by Cryptec Inc. in secret, in collaboration with the United States government. The government had begun constructing extra-solar spaceships without the knowledge of the public ten years prior, and the program consisted of accelerating this construction and loading them with ARC units.

A total of five ships were built as part of the ARC fleet. The first one was the biggest, and contained one thousand occupants, while each subsequent ship housed one hundred occupants each. The occupants of each ship were selected according to the principles outlined by Dr. Carl Schneider in his paper "The Principles of the Selection for the Continuation of the Human Species". While the other occupants slept, the Captain of the ARC I maintained the operation of the ship; the other ships were each assigned a "Warden" for this role. These individuals were selected for their natural immunity to the disease, a rare quality estimated to be possessed by no more than 0.01% of the population.

> north

> north

Museum

You are in a small, circular room. A couple of objects lie around the room, with golden plaques beneath each. You are reminded of the small, hipster galleries you and Isabelle used to go to whenever you travelled to Europe.

You can see a Display Case, a Statue, an Art Piece and a Painting.
You can go south or north.
> x statue

> x statue
It's in the style of a Roman bust. Intelligent eyes, round spectacles . . . with a shock you realize the face is that of Dr. Schneider. You read the plaque below:

Dr. Carl Schneider 1955-2024
Dr. Carl Schneider was born in Rotterdam, Netherlands, and immigrated to the United States with his parents when he was ten. Throughout his life, Dr. Schneider was a cardiologist, university lecturer, and an infectious diseases expert, but he was best known for his role as Chief Scientist at Cryptec Inc., and as the mastermind behind the Selection. When the grey death pandemic broke out in 2020, he lead Cryptec Inc. as the first private entity to create and test cryonic chambers on infected patients. His widely controversial paper, "Principles of the Selection for the Continuation of the Human Race", eventually lead to government sanctions on Cryptec Inc. and the ensuing world war. Despite being infected himself, he delayed treatment, instead prolonging his life through medication and therapy. When the ARC program took off to the cosmos, Dr. Carl Schneider chose to stay behind to supervise the manufacturing of cryonic units for the remaining human population. On August 5th, 2024, members of the HEFA militant group broke into his bunker, and he passed away in the ensuing shootout.

> north

> north
You wave the badge in front of you, and the door slides open on silent tracks. Beyond the doorway, all you see is darkness.

Command Room

You've reached the front of the spaceship. You feel as if you've just entered the Star Room again, but instead of being spherical, this room is shaped like a cone. Sandwiched between a white floor and ceiling is a strip of star-speckled darkness, stretching from left to right across the peripheries of your vision. As you step up, holographic displays flare up all around you, turning the observation glass into a giant display.  Directly in front of you, the black-and-white logo of the ARC flashes impatiently. "You have an incoming message," says the voice that sounds so like Isabelle. "Urgent message incoming. Please receive."

You can see a Display.
You can go south.

The holographic display to your left shows a grid of square photos, each labelled with a name. As you look at them longer you realize that they are live video footage of each of the rooms on the ship. In the square labelled "Dr. Conor Chase", you see your cozy bedroom, just waiting for you to return and take your well-deserved rest. In the square labelled "Greenhouse", you see the Warden still obstinately shovelling at the hard earth."In the square labelled "Sleep Chamber", you see rows upon rows of transparent pods, lined up neatly, their occupants frozen in eternal sleep.
> receive message display

> receive message display
You raise your hand and point at the flashing icon. The display in front of you dissipates into the face of an old woman, so familiar and yet so strange to you. She opens her mouth, and you realize that her voice is the voice of the ship.

"This is Captain Chloe Chase of the ARC One. I am hailing the ARC Two because I haven't received any communications from you in seventy-two hours. We are aware that the ARC Two was hit when we passed through the asteroid field, but our analyses tell us that the hull was not breached. Please respond as soon as possible with your status. If we do not hear from you in twenty-four hours, we will assume the worst and begin emergency measures. Please be advised that it can take up to a week for us to reach you and begin the proper boarding procedures. Captain Chase out."

The display stops. "Auto-playing older messages," Chloe says. "Say anything to cancel."

It's the same face again, but less serious, less stern. This is the playful, sensitive Chloe that you once knew. This is your Chloe.

"Hello, Jake. I hope you are doing well. I know it's been a difficult time for you, ever since Nicole passed away. I should have been there for you more, and I'm truly sorry about that. But today, I want to discuss something happier. I want to talk about the future, not the past. As you know, we've just passed the fifty year mark of our journey, and there is a decision that needs to be made. I have already reached out to the other wardens, just to prepare you before we have any official discussions. I know that all of us have been pondering this for all these long years.

"Shall we go back, or shall we continue? Shall we return to our birthplace, a place we have had no contact with for half a century, and which we now know nothing about? Shall we attempt to clean up the mess we find there, to fix our mistakes of the past? Or shall we continue into the cosmos? Shall we finally let go of our mistakes and start anew? This is the most difficult question I have ever faced, and for now I am undecided. I would not hold it against the other wardens if we were to disagree and diverge in our paths. Please think on this, Jake. I would love to hear your thoughts."

You reach into your pocket and pull out the necklace that you had given Chloe on her twenty-first birthday, and that she had given back to you fifty years ago. The turtle, a symbol for Mother Earth. A symbol for longevity, and for perseverance and stubbornness. Whatever the world was like now, you will not have to face it alone; you will have your daughter beside you. You know what your answer will be.

"But for now, I hope you have the best time." She smiles. "Inbox empty", Chloe says. "Start speaking to respond."

You do.
The End

